You&#39;re talking about [overloads](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/functions.html#overloads) and I think they *are* the conventional way to do this.  

Since TS3.0 or so you could use [rest tuples](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-3-0.html#tuples-in-rest-parameters-and-spread-expressions), [generics](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/generics.html), and [conditional types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-8.html#conditional-types) to avoid overloads, something like this:

    type Callback&lt;T&gt; = (error: Error | null, result: T | void) =&gt; any;
    declare function someFunc2&lt;C extends [Callback&lt;any&gt;] | []&gt;(
        opts: object,
        ...[callback]: C
    ): C extends [Callback&lt;any&gt;] ? void : Promise&lt;any&gt;;
    
    const promiseResult2 = someFunc2({});
    const voidResult2 = someFunc2({}, (e, r) =&gt; r);

But the cure might be worse than the disease here.  I&#39;d stick with overloads, I think, unless your use case really requires single call signatures.  Hope that helps; good luck!

[Link to code](http://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#-ilhk0wH9Wh0ugUivdgIrasr6j8RurNeMQJMUmlZgogA)

