`add_settings_field` is only for one input field. You could find clues in the [reference][1] 

&gt; the callback function needs to output the appropriate html input and
&gt; fill it with the old value, the saving will be done behind the scenes.

For your purpose, I recommend using `add_settings_field` for each of the categories separately, The code would be something like this:

```php
$categories = get_categories(array(
    &#39;orderby&#39; =&gt; &#39;name&#39;,
    &#39;order&#39;   =&gt; &#39;ASC&#39;
));
foreach ($categories as $category) {
    add_settings_field(
        &#39;name_category_&#39; . $category-&gt;cat_ID,
        &#39;Category &#39; . $category-&gt;name,
        &#39;categories_cb&#39;,
        &#39;plugin-settings&#39;,
        &#39;plugin_label_settings&#39;,
        array(
            &#39;id&#39; =&gt; $category-&gt;cat_ID
        )
    );
    register_setting(&#39;plugin-settings&#39;, &#39;name_category_&#39; . $category-&gt;cat_ID);
}

function categories_cb($args)
{
    $settingurl = get_option(&#39;name_category_&#39; . $args[&quot;id&quot;]);
    echo &quot;&lt;input type=&#39;text&#39; name=&#39;name_category_&quot;. $args[&quot;id&quot;] . &quot;&#39; value=&#39;&quot; . $settingurl . &quot;&#39;&gt;&quot;;
}
```

  [1]: https://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/add_settings_field

